102. lt is unnecessary with Miiller, followed by Postgate, to write Graia for Graeca. Graius is perhaps more usual in poets, but Graecus is the only form known to Lucilius, and to Ovid in the Tristia. Propertius uses Graecus: Horace has it twice in the Odes and often in the Epistles and Ars Poetica. Persius Juvenal and Martial use both Graecus and Graius. Tibullus uses neither. Vergil, Statius, and Silius use Graius.
